r, and will continue to do s=\r\no in future. As long as the wheel of existence rotates, old worlds die and =\r\nnew ones are reborn. In each such world there will be a Hanumana, a Rama an=\r\nd a Rama&#39;s ring.&quot;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;-Regards\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0Rajarshi \n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;awaktam =\r\nwyaktimApannam manyantE mAmabuddhayah |\n&gt;&gt;param bhAwamajAnanto mamAwyayaman=\r\nuttamam ||[7:24]\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;________________________________\n&gt;&gt; From: Naras=\r\nimha PVR Rao &lt;pvr@...&gt;\n&gt;&gt;To: vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com \n&gt;&gt;Sent: =\r\nMonday, 30 July 2012 8:16 AM\n&gt;&gt;Subject: [vedic-wisdom] Re: To those who say=\r\n that they don=E2=80=99t believe in any religion\n&gt;&gt; \n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0 \n&gt;&gt;Dear Ra=\r\njarshi,\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;&gt;&lt;&lt;I do not believe in Moksha. What is Moksha? No rebirth=\r\n? If the Universe itself gets born over and over and over, if Rama and Krsh=\r\nna come back at every cycle, who am I to demand that I should not get born?=\r\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;&gt;When we are talking about god, moksha and self-realization, w=\r\nhat we understand of those words/concepts is influenced by our conditioning=\r\n. As our conditioning becomes lighter, our understanding gets refined.\n&gt;&gt;=\r\n=C2=A0\n&gt;&gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;&gt;One person who values power may see god =\r\nas one with this power and that power. One person who values love and kindn=\r\ness may see god as one who is loving and kind to all. One person who values=\r\n freedom may see god as one who is completely free. One person who values k=\r\nnowledge may see god as one who knows everything. And so on. Though all the=\r\nse may be true to some extent, none of them capture the concept of god well=\r\n.\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;&gt;One person with fear or distaste for rebirth may think that mo=\r\nksha is freedom from rebirth. One person with distaste for action may think=\r\n that moksha is freedom from action. One person who is fascinated by happin=\r\ness may think that moksha is supreme happiness. And so on. Though all these=\r\n may be true to some extent, none of them capture the concept of moksha wel=\r\nl.\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;&gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;&gt;One cannot understand liberation w=\r\nithout first understanding what binds one. Liberation is overcoming what bi=\r\nnds one. What binds us and what limits our thinking?\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;&gt;The eight b=\r\nondages/nooses (ashta pashas) are what bind us. The six enemies (shadripus)=\r\n are what fight us as we try to loosen the nooses.\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;&gt;If one works =\r\non loosening the nooses and fighting the enemies, that is the best one can =\r\ndo to progress towards moksha. Thinking about moksha or analyzing it may no=\r\nt be helpful.\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;&gt;Best regards,\n&gt;&gt;Narasimha\n&gt;&gt;--------\n&gt;&gt;Astrology &=\r\n Spirituality Resources: http://www.VedicAstrologer.org\n&gt;&gt;--------\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0=\r\n\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;&gt;On Sun, Jul 29, 2012 at 4:49 PM, rajarshi nandy wrote:\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;Dea=\r\nr Laxmi Narayan ji, \n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;Thank you for your email. I am doing fine and =\r\nI hope you are doing fine too. \n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;Disagreements and difference of view-p=\r\noints are absolutely fine, afterall in ancient India from the monotheists t=\r\no the atheists, we had every breed coexisting. Having said that, I will exp=\r\nlain a few of the points you have raised in your email, from my perspective=\r\n of course. \n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&lt;&lt; You have to complete the story.&gt;. \n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;The r=\r\neason I cannot add anything more to it is because the individ